IE4/5 allow to call 
  elementReference.click()
to simulate a mouse click on all elements which allow an onclick event handler, 
e.g. links, radio buttons, checkboxes.
NN2/3/4 for some unexplained reasons have the click method only for radio 
buttons and checkboxes but not for links for example. 
I think NN5 should do away with this asymmetry and provide a click method for 
all elements it provides an onclick handler for.
It is quite often that you want to click a link with js, till now you have to 
write something alike

<SCRIPT LANGUAGE="JavaScript1.2">
function linkClick () {
  var executeAction = true;
  if (this.onclick) {
    executeAction = this.onclick({type: 'click'});
  }
  if (executeAction) 
    open (this.href, this.target ? this.target : '_self');
}
function initLinkClick () {
  if (document.layers && document.links.length > 0)
    document.links[0].constructor.prototype.click = linkClick;
}
</SCRIPT>
</HEAD>
<BODY ONLOAD="initLinkClick();">

to get that working with NN4. That is unnecessarily complicated for a rather 
simple thing the browser DOM api should provide.

